|+ Example conjugations in the imperative.
|}
Except for the strictly passive binyaním ({{IPA|puˈʕal}} and {{IPA|hufˈʕal}}), each binyan has distinct imperative forms in the second person. This imperative form is only used for affirmative commands. The pa'al, nif'al, pi'el and hif'il form their imperatives by dropping the initial ת [[tav (letter)|taw]] of the future-tense form (e.g., {{hebrew|תִּפְתַּח}} {{IPA|/tifˈtaħ/}} (singular, masc.) → {{hebrew|פְּתַח}} {{IPA|/ˈpətaħ/}} "open!", {{hebrew|תִּשְׁמְרִי}} {{IPA|/tiʃməˈri/}} (singular, fem.) → {{hebrew|שִׁמְרִי}} {{IPA|/ʃimˈri/}} "guard!"); the fifth, hitpa'el, forms its imperative by replacing this initial {{hebrew|ת}} with {{hebrew|ה}} ({{IPA|/titbaˈtːel/}} → {{IPA|/hitbaˈtːel/}} "do nothing!"). (Note that the dropping of the initial ת often results in a change in vocalization, as can be seen in the instance of {{IPA|/tiʃməˈri/}} vs. {{IPA|/ʃ'''i'''mˈri/}}).

Negative commands use the particle {{hebrew|אַל}} {{IPA|/ʔal/}} followed by the future-tense form. For example, {{hebrew|אַל תִּדְאַג}} {{IPA|/ʔal tidʔaɡ/}} means "don't worry" (masculine, singular).

In informal speech, the future tense is commonly used for affirmative commands when making requests. Thus for example, {{hebrew|תִּפְתַּח}} {{IPA|/tifˈtaħ/}} can mean either "you will open" or "would you open" (masculine, singular). (Similarly in English one might say "would you open" or "could you open" in lieu of simply "open".) In Hebrew, as in English, the more formal way to avoid the implication of commanding is to use the word "please" ({{hebrew|בְּבַקָּשָׁה}} {{IPA|/bə-vakːaʃa/}}) with the imperative.

The infinitive can be used as a "general imperative" when addressing nobody in particular (e.g., on signs, or when giving general instructions to children or large groups), so that for example, {{hebrew|נָא לֹא לִפְתֹּחַ}} {{IPA|/ˈna ˈlo lifˈtoaħ/}} means "please do not open". This might be more literally rendered as "it is requested that [this] not be opened", avoiding the question of address by using a passive voice.

==Participles==
Present participles are identical to present tense forms (the modern present tense actually having been derived from the ancient present participle): {{hebrew|נֵרוֹת בּוֹעֲרִים}} {{IPA|/neˈrot boʕaˈrim/}} (burning candles), {{hebrew|יַלְדָּה מַקְסִימָה}} {{IPA|/jalˈda maksiˈma/}} (charming girl).

Only the pa'al binyan has a true past participle: from {{hebrew|כתב}} k-t-b we have {{hebrew|כָּתוּב}} {{IPA|/kaˈtuv/}}, (writ, written). For verbs that have a pa'al form and a nif'al form serving as its passive, this provides a means to distinguish between a completed and a continuing action. The pa'al past participle indicates completion:

*{{hebrew|הַסְּפָרִים כְּתוּבִים}} {{IPA|/hasː(ə)faˈrim k(ə)tuˈvim/}} (the books are written)

while the present tense of nif'al indicates that the action continues:

*{{hebrew|הַסְּפָרִים נִכְתָּבִים}} {{IPA|/hasː(ə)faˈrim nixtaˈvim/}} (the books are being written)

The passive participle is commonly used as an adjective, as in {{hebrew|הַפְּקֻדָּה הַכְּתוּבָה}} {{IPA|/hapː(ə)kuˈd:a hakː(ə)tuˈva/}} (the written order).

The present tense of the pu'al and huf'al are used as passive participles for the pi'el and hif'il respectively. For example, from hif'il {{hebrew|הֵאִיר}} {{IPA|/heˈʔir/}} (lit) we get {{hebrew|חֶדֶר מוּאָר}} {{IPA|/ˈħeder muˈʔar/}} (lit room).

==Infinitives (Prospectives)==
Infinitives ({{IPA|/ʃəˈmot hapːoˈʕal/}}) in Hebrew are primarily formed by adding the letter lamed (ל) to the front of the base form ({{IPA|/t͡suˈrat hamːaˈkor/}}). The vowels change systematically according to the binyan.

*{{hebrew|כָּתַב}} {{IPA|/kaˈtav/}} (wrote, {{IPA|paʕal}}) → {{hebrew|לִכְתֹּב}} {{IPA|/lixˈtov/}} (to write)
*{{hebrew|מְדַבֵּר}} {{IPA|/mədaˈb:er/}} (speak, {{IPA|piʕel}}) → {{hebrew|לְדַבֵּר}} {{IPA|/lədaˈbːer/}} (to speak)
*{{hebrew|הִתְחִיל}} {{IPA|/hitˈħil/}} (started, {{IPA|hifʕil}}) → {{hebrew|לְהַתְחִיל}} {{IPA|/ləhatˈħil/}} (to start)
*{{hebrew|הִתְפַּלֵּל}} {{IPA|/hitpaˈlːel/}} (prayed, {{IPA|hitpaʕel}}) → {{hebrew|לְהִתְפַּלֵּל}} {{IPA|/ləhitpaˈlːel/}} (to pray)
*{{hebrew|נִפְגַשׁ}} {{IPA|/nifˈɡaʃ/}} (met with, {{IPA|nifʕal}}) → {{hebrew|לְהִפָּגֵשׁ}} {{IPA|/ləhipːaˈɡeʃ/}} (to meet with)

Note that {{IPA|puʕal}} and {{IPA|hufʕal}} verbs do not have infinitives.

==Gerunds==
Gerunds ({{IPA|ʃəˈmot pəʕuˈla}}) are nouns expressing an action. Gerunds are created in Hebrew by putting the root of a verb into a {{IPA|miʃˈkal}}, a noun pattern (''see'' [[Modern Hebrew grammar#Noun derivation]]). Five of the binyanim have gerunds: {{IPA|paʕal}}, {{IPA|piʕel}}, {{IPA|hifʕil}}, {{IPA|hitpaʕel}}, and {{IPA|nifʕal}}. For example:

*{{hebrew|שָׁמַר}} {{IPA|/ʃaˈmar/}} (''guarded'' — {{IPA|paˈʕal}}) → {{hebrew|שְׁמִירָה}} {{IPA|/ʃ(ə)miˈra/}} (''guarding, a watch'')
**{{hebrew|שָׁב}} {{IPA|/ˈʃav/}} (''returned'' — hollow {{IPA|paʕal}}) → {{hebrew|שִׁיבָה}} {{IPA|/ʃiˈva/}} (''returning'', ''a return'')
**{{hebrew|שָׁתָה}} {{IPA|/ʃaˈta/}} (''drank'' — final hey {{IPA|paʕal}}) → {{hebrew|שְׁתִיָּה}} {{IPA|/ʃ(ə)tiˈjːa/}} (''drinking'', ''a drink'')
*{{hebrew|נִכְנַס}} {{IPA|/nixˈnas/}} (''enter'' — {{IPA|nifʕal}}) → {{hebrew|הִכָּנְסוּת}} {{IPA|/hikːanˈsut/}} (''entering, an entrance'')
*{{hebrew|בִּקֵּר}} {{IPA|/biˈkːer/}} (''visited'' — {{IPA|piʕel}}) → {{hebrew|בִּקּוּר}} {{IPA|/biˈkːur/}} (''visiting'', ''a visit'')
*{{hebrew|הִפְתִּיעַ}} {{IPA|/hifˈtiaʕ/}} (''surprised'' — {{IPA|hifʕil}}) → {{hebrew|הַפְתָעָה}} {{IPA|/haftaˈʕa/}} (''surprising'', ''a surprise'')
*{{hebrew|הִתְחַמֵּם}} {{IPA|/hitħaˈmːem/}} (''warmed'' — {{IPA|hitpaʕel}}) → {{hebrew|הִתְחַמְּמוּת}} {{IPA|/hitħamːəˈmut/}} (''warming'')

Note that unlike in English (where gerunds and present participles share the same form but different etymology), Hebrew gerunds cannot be used as adjectives.

==Conditional==
Modern Hebrew has an analytic [[conditional mood|conditional]]~[[Habitual aspect|past-habitual mood]] expressed with the auxiliary {{IPA|/haˈja/}}:

