{{Infobox language |name=Opuuo |nativename=T'apo |states=[[Ethiopia]] |region=Along the [[Ethiopia]]–[[South Sudan]] border |speakers={{sigfig|5000|2}} in Ethiopia |date=2007 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=[[Komuz languages|Komuz]] |fam3=[[Koman languages|Koman]] |iso3=lgn |glotto=opuu1239 |glottorefname=Opuuo }}
The '''Opuo''' language is a [[Nilo-Saharan languages|Nilo-Saharan language]] spoken by the [[Shita]] of [[Ethiopia]] and [[South Sudan]]. It is a member of the [[Koman languages]], and has a lexical similarity of 24% with [[Komo language|Komo]]. The language is also called Opo-Shita, Opo, Opuo, Cita, Ciita, Shita, Shiita, Ansita, Kina, and Kwina. The self-name for the language is T'apo. "Langa" is a derogatory term for its speakers used by the [[Anuak people|Anuak]].<ref name=e18/>
Ethiopian speakers live in five villages along the South Sudan border north of the Anuak and [[Nuer people|Nuer]], and its South Sudanese in [[Upper Nile State]], around [[Kigille]] and [[Maiwut]];<ref name=e18/> however, of the 286 speakers the 1994 Ethiopian Census records, 183 are in the [[Oromia Region]] (mostly in the [[Mirab Shewa Zone]]), 32 in the [[Southern Nations, Nationalities, and People's Region]], and less than ten in either of the Regions closest to South Sudan.<ref>[http://www.csa.gov.et/surveys/Population%20and%20Housing%20Census%201994/survey0/index.html "The 1994 Population and Housing Census of Ethiopia"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207032949/http://www.csa.gov.et/surveys/Population%20and%20Housing%20Census%201994/survey0/index.html |date=2008-12-07 }} (accessed 31 January 2009)</ref>
