[[File:Jan Vilímek - Sofie Podlipská HL.jpg|thumb|Czech writer Sofie Podlipská]]
'''Sofie Podlipská''' (1833-1897<ref name="Hawkesworth2001">{{cite book|author=C. Hawkesworth|title=A History of Central European Women's Writing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dPOFDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA54|date=10 April 2001|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=978-0-333-98515-1|pages=54-55, 132-133}}</ref>) was a Czech writer and the sister of [[Karolina Světlá]]. Sofie Podlipská mostly wrote historical novels, juvenile works, and [[feminist literature]].<ref name="Hrbkova1920">{{cite book|author=Šárka B. Hrbkova|title=Czechoslovak Stories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fCs7AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA41|year=1920|publisher=Duffield|page=41}}</ref> She also had an interest in [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophy]] <ref name="Cornis-PopeNeubauer2010">{{cite book|author1=Marcel Cornis-Pope|author2=John Neubauer|title=History of the Literary Cultures of East-Central Europe: Junctures and disjunctures in the 19th and 20th centuries. Volume IV: Types and stereotypes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7T8zAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA350|date=29 September 2010|publisher=John Benjamins Publishing Company|isbn=978-90-272-8786-1|page=350}}</ref> and helped found the "American Ladies' Club." The name had no geographical meaning instead the word "American" was to designate it as modern and for progress.<ref>[http://www.radio.cz/en/section/special/a-brave-few-women-the-forgotten-legacy-of-the-american-ladies-club-in-prague Radio Prague]</ref> Her work emphasized motherhood and morality.<ref name="Paletschek2005">{{cite book|author=Sylvia Paletschek|title=Women's Emancipation Movements in the Nineteenth Century: A European Perspective|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V-M6xJTquioC&pg=PA174|date=14 November 2005|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-6707-1|page=174}}</ref>
